04408nam a22006975i 9780226331898DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20172016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263318987 a10.7208/97802263318982doi  a(DE-B1597)523510  a(OCoLC)993765658  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aARC0000002bisacsh04a720.954562231 aRajagopalan, Mrinalini, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBuilding Histories :bThe Archival and Affective Lives of Five Monuments in Modern Delhi /cMrinalini Rajagopalan. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b10 color plates, 51 halftones,  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSouth Asia Across the Disciplines00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tNote on Transliteration -- tINTRODUCTION: The Modern Lives of Medieval Monuments between Archive and Affect -- t1. 1857: Red Fort. Mutiny, Memory, Monument -- t2. Rasul Numa Dargah. Interrupting the Archive: Indigenous Voices and Colonial Hegemony -- t3. 1932: Jama Masjid. A Menacing Mosque Reveals the Limits of Colonial Power -- t4. 1948: Purana Qila. The Many Origins of Partitioned Nations, Cities, and Monuments -- t5. 2000: Qutb Complex. Secular Nations and Specters of Iconoclasm -- tEPILOGUE: Making New Monuments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBuilding Histories offers innovative accounts of five medieval monuments in Delhi-the Red Fort, Rasul Numa Dargah, Jama Masjid, Purana Qila, and the Qutb complex-tracing their modern lives from the nineteenth century into the twentieth. Mrinalini Rajagopalan argues that the modern construction of the history of these monuments entailed the careful selection, manipulation, and regulation of the past by both the colonial and later postcolonial states. Although framed as objective "archival" truths, these histories were meant to erase or marginalize the powerful and persistent affective appropriations of the monuments by groups who often existed outside the center of power. By analyzing these archival and affective histories together, Rajagopalan works to redefine the historic monument-far from a symbol of a specific past, the monument is shown in Building Histories to be a culturally mutable object with multiple stories to tell.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aArchitecture - Political aspects - India - New Delhi. 0aArchitecturexPolitical aspectszIndiazNew Delhi. 0aIslamic architecturezIndiazNew Delhi. 4aASI. 4aArchaeological Survey of India. 4aDelhi. 4aJama Masjid. 4aPurana Qila. 4aQutb Minar. 4aRasul Numa Dargah. 4aRed Fort. 4aarchitecture. 4acolonial histories. 4apreservation. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226331898423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226331898.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles